{"sections":{"listicle_wCzMw7":{"type":"listicle","blocks":{"header_Tt4Mbf":{"type":"header","settings":{"title":"4 Ways to Make Screens Feel Easier on Your Eyes","title_size":48,"title_font_weight":700,"title_line_height":1.2,"title_alignment":"left","title_color":"#25282a","title_margin_top":0,"title_margin_bottom":10,"show_author_info":true,"author_avatar":"shopify:\/\/shop_images\/Frame_14.png","author_name":"Parlay Optics","author_date":"December 28th, 2025","avatar_size":50,"author_gap":16,"author_alignment":"flex-start","author_name_size":16,"author_name_font_weight":600,"author_name_color":"#25282a","author_name_force_bold":true,"author_date_size":14,"author_date_font_weight":400,"author_date_color":"#25282a","author_margin_bottom":25,"header_margin_top":30,"header_margin_bottom":0,"mobile_title_size":40,"mobile_author_name_size":16,"mobile_author_date_size":14}},"summary_hpMNBU":{"type":"summary","settings":{"summary_text":"<p>Most people don’t think about artificial light — until their eyes feel tired, overstimulated, or wired late at night.<\/p><p>Screens are everywhere. Indoor lighting is constant. And modern life doesn’t really shut off.<\/p><p>You don’t need to move off-grid.<\/p><p>You don’t need rigid rules.<\/p><p>Here are four realistic ways people reduce the intensity of artificial light in everyday life.<\/p>","summary_margin_top":15,"summary_margin_bottom":20}},"listicle_item_RtCU4x":{"type":"listicle_item","settings":{"enable_container":false,"image":"shopify:\/\/shop_images\/Screenshot_2025-12-28_at_11.31.34_PM.png","hide_image":false,"title":"1. Turn screens down — but don’t fight them","content":"<p>Lowering brightness helps, but only to a point.<\/p><p>Most people still need screens for work, messages, and winding down.<\/p><p>Brightness adjustments help in the moment, but they don’t change how artificial light feels over long days.<\/p><p>This is a good first step.<\/p><p>It’s just not the whole answer.<\/p>","highlight_text":"","image_position":"left","mobile_image_position":"bottom","image_aspect_ratio":"square","item_gap":25,"item_image_width":225,"item_image_border_radius":6,"item_image_margin_bottom":16,"item_background_color":"#ffffff","item_padding":25,"item_border_radius":8,"item_border_width":1,"item_border_color":"#d9ecfc","enable_item_shadow":false,"item_shadow":"0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.1)","highlight_background_color":"#fcdef4","highlight_text_color":"#25282a","highlight_padding":8,"highlight_border_radius":4,"highlight_margin_top":10}},"listicle_item_zDcz3V":{"type":"listicle_item","settings":{"enable_container":false,"hide_image":true,"title":"2. Be mindful of lighting — when it’s easy","content":"<p>Switching harsh overhead lights for softer lamps can make a difference.<\/p><p>But no one controls every environment they’re in.<\/p><p>Offices, stores, gyms, restaurants — artificial light is everywhere.<\/p><p>Lighting awareness helps.<\/p><p>Avoiding it completely isn’t realistic.<\/p>","highlight_text":"","image_position":"left","mobile_image_position":"top","image_aspect_ratio":"square","item_gap":25,"item_image_width":250,"item_image_border_radius":6,"item_image_margin_bottom":16,"item_background_color":"#ffffff","item_padding":25,"item_border_radius":12,"item_border_width":1,"item_border_color":"#d9ecfc","enable_item_shadow":false,"item_shadow":"0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.1)","highlight_background_color":"#fcdef4","highlight_text_color":"#25282a","highlight_padding":8,"highlight_border_radius":4,"highlight_margin_top":10}},"listicle_item_gfdexG":{"type":"listicle_item","settings":{"enable_container":false,"hide_image":true,"title":"3. Give your eyes distance from artificial light","content":"<p>This is where most people notice the biggest shift.<\/p><p>Not blocking screens. Not eliminating light.<\/p><p>Just creating <em>distance<\/em> from it.<\/p><p>Reducing glare.Softening intensity.Letting the visual environment feel calmer.<\/p><p>For many people, this comes down to what they wear on their face.<\/p>","highlight_text":"","image_position":"left","mobile_image_position":"top","image_aspect_ratio":"square","item_gap":25,"item_image_width":250,"item_image_border_radius":6,"item_image_margin_bottom":16,"item_background_color":"#ffffff","item_padding":25,"item_border_radius":8,"item_border_width":1,"item_border_color":"#620a0a","enable_item_shadow":false,"item_shadow":"0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.1)","highlight_background_color":"#620a0a","highlight_text_color":"#ffffff","highlight_padding":8,"highlight_border_radius":4,"highlight_margin_top":10}},"listicle_item_4Jy6iC":{"type":"listicle_item","settings":{"enable_container":false,"image":"shopify:\/\/shop_images\/Frame_14.png","hide_image":false,"title":"4. Choose lenses designed for modern light","content":"<p>Parlay Optics was created for people who live indoors, work on screens, and scroll at night — without wanting wellness hype or exaggerated claims.<\/p><p>Parlay offers two intentional lens options:<\/p><p><strong>The Everyday Lens<\/strong><\/p><p>Balanced reduction. Designed to soften artificial light while keeping colors natural. Easy to wear all day.<\/p><p><strong>The Sleep Enhancer Lens<\/strong><\/p><p>Greater reduction. A warmer, calmer visual environment. Often chosen in the evening or whenever you want more distance from screens. <\/p><p>Neither is better. They’re different levels of intention.<\/p><h3><strong>Why people choose Parlay<\/strong><\/h3><p>Parlay doesn’t promise to fix your sleep. It doesn’t claim medical breakthroughs.<\/p><p>It simply makes artificial light feel easier to live with.<\/p><p>Quiet relief. Thoughtful design. Built for modern routines.<\/p>","highlight_text":"","image_position":"left","mobile_image_position":"top","image_aspect_ratio":"square","item_gap":25,"item_image_width":250,"item_image_border_radius":6,"item_image_margin_bottom":16,"item_background_color":"#ffffff","item_padding":25,"item_border_radius":8,"item_border_width":1,"item_border_color":"#d9ecfc"